node.text:
A snippet from this awesome piece by Kathleen Farmilo:
. . . . .
"Without clubs, bars and crucially, other people, I haven’t been able to go down the tried and tested route of a club or a bar or a pub where someone is interested in me. Even dating apps have fizzled. While I have done my share of swiping, not being able to meet people in person makes it hard to keep conversations alive.
. . . . . .
It’s been an important moment – understanding how to be okay with not wanting a relationship. And learning that the antithesis of that is not always throwing yourself into casual flings.
. . . . . .
For me, it’s been a time to learn how to be alone without any external validation of my attractiveness, my funniness or my worth as a person. Those deep-seated insecurities are alleviated when you’re being dated or flirted with. Now, I’ve had to learn how to draw from that within myself."

node.text:
As I wrote the post about expectations a few months ago in the middle of lockdown, I thought it would be helpful to reflect how things have changed since then. When thinking about this, two words came to mind...Time and Adjustment. 

I started thinking how much pressure we can put on ourselves to be perfect in every role we play, whether that be mum, dad, child, employee, and then feel guilty for not feeling quite up to what we think is "standard".

Time - We sometimes don't give ourselves the time to learn, to make mistakes, for bonds to form and for our strength to rebuild. With the passing of these months I have learnt so much, about my baby, about me, about motherhood and that everything changes all of the time! This has influenced my mindset and my confidence in my abilities as a Mum. 

Over this time I have also Adjusted to the role of Mum; new routines, household chores, functioning on less sleep, learning new skills and knowledge, whether that be play, baby sleep or weaning, and being able to make time for friends and family. Don't get me wrong, i don't succeed at all of this all of the time, but I think it is getting alot better.

Looking back I may not have given myself a fair chance at the beginning and I see that now. We all need to give ourselves the chance to grow in whatever roles we have and know it can be peaks and troths all the way (especially with sleep üôà!). 

This taught me to remember to be patient with myself, stay more in the present moment and I know it sounds cliched, but take each day as it comes and do what I can, and again know that's enough. So essentially the same message as previously, that what you're doing is enough and to give ourselves a chance.

xx

‚ú®ROCKS‚ú®
New York has the COOLEST rock formations left from the melting of Ice Age glaciers—some of the best of which are at Watkins Glen State Park. The park is known for its Gorge Trail, which runs along the stream (Glen Creek) that was responsible for cutting through the clearly seen layers of sedimentary rock. Here in Upstate NY, we’re so lucky to have awesome examples of the different types of sciences we learn about while in primary/secondary school. üôåüèª 
Watkins Glen was a great “hike” to spend our Monday morning doing, and I was veeerrryyyy stoked that a majority of people were wearing their masks along the busy trail!

Over supplied with green stuff this week so watercress and spinach soup for the freezer then for fast days üíö

Dinner was a new one from @missminifer The Green Roasting Tin. Posh cheesy chips with Stilton and hazelnuts. Splendid.

node.text:
- Lockdown -
 
Each post on my grid from 6th May - 21st July is a picture taken from one location: home. I’m a big believer of making the best of what you’ve got so that’s what I decided to do on my grid to get me through Lockdown. Prior to that as Lockdown in the U.K. began in March, I looked through old photos and posted.

Apart from perhaps two posts, I’ve not specifically documented life inside or outside the ‘bubble’ we’ve been living in. 

- Now -

This is us travelling into a part of London for the first time post Lockdown, where I knew I’d find the events of the past few months visibly documented. Bearing witness to these feels so very important right now, as restrictions are greater eased and we begin to learn to live this new life of ‘normal’. Looking after each other and ourselves is still as important as ever; an aspect of Lockdown which I don’t want to forget.

LIFTER SHOWCASE 

@shane_olylift straight out of lockdown with a 320 squat, 180 bench and 300 deadlift with plenty more in the tank 

For those who don’t know, Shane was one of the best raw junior powerlifters in the country and has been lifting since he was like 12 !

Shane dropped weight and actually did some  cardio for once (it turns out powerlifters can run ??!!) and qualified to be a firefighter for the London fire service. He also turned his hand to Olympic lifting and qualified as a coach in this discipline too and is available powerlifting and Olympic lifting at Bulks Power & Strength Gym

He’s now going back to his roots...

Whatever happens in life; just get strong. It seems to solve most problems üòòüòò

On #day149 of #bushlife #lockdown we were planning on darting a Buffalo to remove a piece of wire from his foot, but by the time the vet arrived the wire was off and it wasn't necessary anymore. Whilst we were watching the Buffalo herd at a waterhole though, an old Elephant bull showed up as well as some Warthog, Waterbuck, Zebra, Wildebeest, Nyala and Kudu and there were 2 male Cheetahs nearby. Not as exciting as darting a wild animal, but a pretty amazing sighting to have and a chance to sit quietly and enjoy the tranquility of nature...

node.text:
What an incredible five months it’s been since lockdown started on 23rd March!  Three days before my 50th birthday and I definitely feel older and wiser five months in!  We’ve had the joy of seeing first hand the ‘learning’ characters of our three stars - their resilience and determination. We’ve watched and supported their anxieties and uncertainties and fielded our own. We’ve home-schooled, counselled and worked from home and I’ve learnt more about our wider family, our Altfield family too. Colleagues who have stepped up to the plate to go above and beyond to make sure samples go out, orders and quotes are put together, clients are supported, suppliers are updated and morale is as high as it can be.  Colleagues who have accepted furlough and taken it in their stride, keeping in touch with each other and making sure everyone is ok. We are facing some sad farewells and are going to miss our teammates hugely. With all the massive positives, the true spirit of Altfield coming to the fore, we will not let anything spoil the view.  This incredible rainbow in the somewhat threatening sky this afternoon just summed up how I feel ..: just as the children have shown us how to keep ones head down and carry on, we will too.  After all, knowing in your heart that you have done your best - and done your best by others as well - is all that really matters at the end of the day. 

Here’s to the rest of the year ahead of us!

node.text:
The last thing I did before leaving the office the day the Covid lockdown was announced in France was to order some cookbooks, thinking I would put the "free time" to good use. OH INNOCENT PAST ME. 

Sidenote : I want to give a big warm shout-out to all the Toddler Parents who have made it this far without murdering their offspring and/or each other üôåüèª

Anyway. This beautiful book, Fika by @annabrones and @johannakindvall had been on my wishlist for ages, and it arrived about a week into lockdown. I had chosen it because of my obsession with cinnamon rolls and my inability to get them right, and the recipe in this book is perfect. And delicious. And I baked it a lot.

But unexpectedly,  the best thing I discovered about this book is that it is written specifically with the goal of preparing the recipes as simply as possible, without a stand mixer or much in the way of fancy tools. A number of the recipes essentially entail stirring things together, making it an excellent source of recipes to cook with toddlers who like to help in the kitchen. My daughter absolutely loves cooking (in fact one of her earliest words was "whisk" üòÜ) and this gave us a few projects during those interminable days during lockdown where she needed to be entertained quietly and indoors. 

The first recipe we tried from this book was the Fyriskaka, an apple cake spiced with cinnamon and cardamom. I baked that again today, because I had the house to myself while Husband and Toddler went to the park. It is lovely and I recommend it, whether you have a toddler to entertain or not. 

(However I think there is a global conspiracy involving food stylists and  cakes that involve concentric circles of Apple slices - if you can get your Apple slices to stay in concentric circles before during and after baking, you are practising witchcraft of some kind üßôüèª‍‚ôÄÔ∏è)

node.text:
Anyone else tired of wearing the same thing every day? 

PS @neonaise thinks this is normal but the  slight desperation I felt to do it freaked me out so much so that I kept it to myself for some time. She was like “no girl, it’s fine dress up, put some make up on and take some selfies! “ I’ve always struggled with selfies. I associated it with vanity. Now to dress up, put make up on AND take a selfie with nowhere to go? Nah... I’m too practical for that. But what’s wrong with feeling good and taking a good selfie? I’ll work myself up to do it one day.

node.text:
New Zealand’s High Court has ruled that the country’s first nine-day, Covid-19 lockdown from March 26 to April 3 was unlawful as it infringed on people’s rights and freedoms without a legal basis.

The High Court of New Zealand ruled on Wednesday that the country’s stay-at-home orders, under threat of punishment, were in breach of civil liberties after lawyer Andrew Borrowdale launched a suit against the government in July.

A panel of three judges waved off a number of associated complaints but conceded that authorities should have written the order into law before using the threat of police detention to keep people inside. 

“While there is no question that the requirement was a necessary, reasonable and proportionate response to the Covid-19 crisis at the time, the requirement was not prescribed by law and was therefore contrary to section 5 of the New Zealand Bill of Rights Act,” the ruling read.

The solution is to find the level in yourself that is fearless. This level lies deep within. On the surface, the mind is unruly and agitated by the effects of anxiety. On the layer below that, the voice of fear dwells on risks, failure, and worst-case scenarios.

Only when you can transcend this level do you reach the true self, which views every situation without fear. This is because fear comes from the past, arising from the memory of pain. The true self lives in the present; therefore it has no contact with old hurts and wounds.

We just need to keep moving forward. We, like time, cannot stop

We’re surrounded by so much uncertainty these days, and even with my exhausting levels of #energy and my annoying (to some) omnipresent #optimism, I am finding it challenging sometimes to keep a positive outlook.  I often find myself trying to silence that small voice in my head that keeps luring me into procrastinating or even giving up on ideas altogether : "I'm waiting for the right time"

"I'm waiting for all this to be over so we can go back to how things were"

"I'm waiting for things to go back to normal"

"I'm waiting for the right opportunity" 

Many of us have been waiting for the right moment..waiting out the #pandemic, waiting for a #vaccine, waiting for the job market or economy to pick up... But what have you been doing in the mean time? 

Because time hasn't stopped. How can we do things differently? How can we still go ahead with our plans or #goals? You just need to get started. That's all it takes. 

There is no big grand plan needed in 2020. It’s day by day and small steps all the way for me üôèüèªü§ç ... ÿ≠ÿ™Ÿâ ÿßŸÑŸÑŸá ŸäŸÅÿ±ÿ¨Ÿáÿß ÿπŸÑŸäŸÜÿß ü§çü§ç #life #love #instagood #like #instagram #happy #design #smile #photography #lifestyle #art #me #motivation #covid19 #style  #nature #beautiful #selfie #quotes #picoftheday #photo #lockdown #fashion #curfew #inspiration

.

Reposted from @possibileit Parliamo di #scuola da molto prima che la data del #14settembre divenisse cos√¨ incombente, ma non dimentichiamo che a breve anche gli studenti universitari riprenderanno le #lezioni.

Il tempo stringe e ci si aspetterebbe che fossero pronti piani e protocolli utili a permettere ad un esercito di invisibili di ricominciare il proprio percorso con dignit√† e rispetto, senza venire considerati una spesa improduttiva, incapace di contribuire al funzionamento della societ√† come avviene da sempre, in particolare nell’ultimo anno.

E invece no.

Gli #universitari sono dimenticati non solo dalle istituzioni, ma anche dal dibattito pubblico che, tardivamente, tenta di recuperare mesi di quiescenza sulla scuola.

Un Paese coeso e lungimirante ripartirebbe dalle istituzioni che si occupano di #Istruzione, in grado di restituire alla comunit√† un benessere sociale ed economico, invece ci ritroviamo un Ministro dell’Universit√† assente, allineato con l’idea per cui gli studenti dovrebbero continuare i loro studi come se nulla fosse, nonostante lo stravolgimento metodologico e accettando tacitamente una falsa equit√† nella qualit√† dell’insegnamento e delle esperienze, come se non ci fossero conseguenze sulla completezza degli apprendimenti e come se tutti avessero gli strumenti per usufruire della #didatticaadistanza.

Due settimane fa il Ministro #Manfredi assicurava garanzie e allargamenti nel #dirittoallostudio, svelando per√≤ l'impossibilit√† di una ripresa completa delle lezioni in presenza e vantandosi dell'accresciuto numero di lauree durante il #lockdown.

√à una retorica che sminuisce l’#Universit√† trasformandola in un vero e proprio “esamificio”, dove poco conta il percorso di chi la vive, che viene ridotto a una merce da impacchettare a lanciare in un mondo del lavoro degradato e alienante.

Servono lungimiranza e chiarezza, chi studia non pu√≤ continuare a brancolare nel buio, non sapendo quale sar√† il futuro del suo percorso accademico. Servono priorit√† non guidate da frivoli interessi economici di parte: non vogliamo pi√π vedere facolt√†, #biblioteche, laboratori vuoti, quando tutto il resto ha ripreso un’attivit√† regolare.

Anyone that asks me about fitness I tell them to ignore the scales, the number doesn’t matter, it’s how you look and feel!  Well against my own advice I weighed myself and was alarmed at my weight gain and now feel like crap! Doing exactly what I tell people not to do!
People think I just post selfies like hey look at me.. but actually I have a constant mental battle with food, drink, fitness and self esteem. 
Have dropped from daily training to weekly and feel pretty crap! It’s not too late to turn it around though. Just need a bit of a kick up the arse, some routine and motivation back. #fitness #gym #motivation #mentalhealth #lockdown #kifitness #gymshark #selflove #fitnessmotivation #weighgain
